Climate change is a significant problem that must be addressed immediately. The notion that technical advancement alone will offer enough mitigation is erroneous and perhaps hazardous. While technology may absolutely help with climate change mitigation, it is not a panacea. To begin, it is critical to recognize that human activity is the major driver of climate change, notably the combustion of fossil fuels, which emits greenhouse gases into the atmosphere. While new technology may assist to cut emissions, they will not totally eradicate them. Furthermore, even if new technologies are invented and applied, they will not be able to undo the harm already done. Furthermore, depending entirely on technology to mitigate climate change misses the reality that climate change is a global issue that need a collaborative effort from governments, people, and corporations. Technology alone will not be able to solve the systemic adjustments required to minimize the consequences of climate change. Finally, it is critical to evaluate the possible limits and unexpected effects of over-reliance on technology. New technologies, for example, may be costly and difficult to deploy in developing nations, and they may also have harmful effects on the environment and society. To summarize, fears about climate change are justified, and we must take quick and thorough action to solve this problem. While technology may help with mitigation, it is not a replacement for the systemic reforms and community actions required to address climate change. 